Rating: 0
This is a basic recipe for authentic gumbo. Mr. B's Bistro published "Gumbo Ya-Ya" when the restaurant opened in NO in 1979. BASIC: Most every cook outside of La. NEEDS TO KNOW HOW TO MAKE A GOOD QUALITY ROUX. You may use either butter or good quality vegetable oil, however, this is the basis of every great gumbo. Best to stir the roux up in a black iron skillet, however, La. cooks know how to make it correctly many different ways. Also, south Louisiana gumbo does not have a big (awful) can of tomatoes in it! Again, the secret is in the quality of the dark, mahogany colored roux that you create as the basis for the recipe. Mr. B's Bistro is a prominent New Orleans family owned restaurant, and Gumbo YA YA was a great way to indocrinate tourists to our most famous soup recipe. Also of note, this recipe calls for sausage and chicken. La. chefs do not always make "seafood gumbo" and rely upon duck, chicken, hen, and other ingredients for authentic gumbo. Happy mardi gras.

