Tastes extremely rich, thick, and creamy, but I would never make it again because of the effort required. This was my first time making roux/gumbo. I halved the recipe and used the proportions specified at http://www.mrbsbistro.com/reci.htm: 1 lb. Unsalted butter 1 lb. all-purpose flour The texture seemed just perfect. I used medium-low heat, but after over four hours, the roux had reached only a caramel color, not dark mahogany. Because it was after midnight, I gave up on darkening it further and went ahead and finished the recipe. When I tasted it, I kept perceiving an excess of butter and flour, but that may have been psychological, given that I had been stirring those two ingredients for so long. I would recommend adding more "stuff," especially vegetables. As for the chicken broth, I used 60% canned chicken broth and 40% homemade broth from the chicken bones and the veggie remains.

